he diverse domains in which radio is imagined, deployed, and understood. Drawing on research from six continents, the volume demonstrates how the particular capacities and practices of radio provide singular insight into diverse social worlds, ranging from aboriginal Australia to urban Zambia. Together, the contributors address how radio creates distinct possibilities for rethinking such fundamental concepts as culture, communication, community, and collective agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aCommunication and culturexHistoryx21st century. 0aCommunication and culturexHistoryy21st century. 0aCommunication in anthropologyxHistoryx21st century. 0aCommunication in anthropologyxHistoryy21st century. 0aRadioxHistoryx21st century. 0aRadioxHistoryy21st century. 0aTechnologyxAnthropological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aFisher, Daniel1 aGinsburg, Faye08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769935423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814769935.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK